column3: USDA Economic Research Service Metro/Nonmetro labels
column109: Nonmetro counties include some combination of open countryside, rural towns (places with fewer than 2,500 people), and urban areas with populations rnaging from 2,500 to 49,999 that are not part of larger labor market areas (metropolitan areas).

column3: NC Department of Commerce economic well-being designations
column109: 40 counties are ranked Tier One (most distressed), 40 counties ranked Tier Two, and 20 counties ranked as Tier Three (Least Distressed). Tier rankings use four factors: average unemployment rate for the most recent twelve months for which data are available, median household income for the most recent 12 months for which data are available, percentage growth in population for the most recent 36 months for which data are available, and adjusted property tax rate base per capita for the most recent taxable year.

column3: % of population enrolled in Medicaid or CHIP
column109: The number of Medicaid/Health Choice enrollees were obtained from the Division of Medical Assitance annual unduplicated enrollment count. Percentages were calculated using 2017 county population estimates from the U.S. Census Bureau Population Estimate Program.

column2: Health Care Workforce - Primary Care Physicians
column3: Primary care physicians per 10,000 population
column4: North Carolin Health Professions Data System - Cecil G. Sheps Center for Health Services Research
column109: Data include active licensed pysicians in practice in North Carolina as of October 31 of each year who are not residents-in-training and are not employed by the Federal government. Physician data are derived from the North Carolina Board of Medicine. County estimates are based on primary practice location. Population census data and estimates are downloaded from the North Carolina Office of State Budget and Management via NC LINC and are based on US Census data.

column3: Dentists per 10,000 population
column4: North Carolina Health Preofessions Data System - Cecil G. Sheps Center for Health Services Research
column109: Data include active, licensed dentists in practice in North Carolina as of October 31 of each year. Dentist data are derived from the North Carolina State Board of Dental Examiners. Population census data and estimates are downloaded from the North Carolina Office of State Budget and Management via NC LINC and are based on US Census data.

column3: Psychiatrists- all specialties & psychologists per 10,000 population
column4: North Carolina Health Preofessions Data System - Cecil G. Sheps Center for Health Services Research
column109: Data include active licensed physicians, who are not residents-in training and are not employed by the Federal govermnet, and active licensed psychologists in practice in North Carolina as of October 31 of each year. Physician data are derived from the North Carolina Board of Medicine. Psychologist data are derived from the North Carolina Psychology Board. Population census data and estimates are downloaded from the North Carolina Office of State Budget and Management via NC LINC and are based on US Census data.

column3: OBGYNs/family medicine physicians/CNMs per 10,000 population
column4: North Carolina Health Preofessions Data System - Cecil G. Sheps Center for Health Services Research
column109: Data include active, licensed physicians, who are not in residency training and are not employed by the Federal government, and certified nurse midwives in practice in North Carolina as of October 31, 2016. Data are derived from the license and reregistration files from the NC Medical Board and the NC Midwifery Joint Committee. County of practice is based on self-reported primary practice location. Physicians are included who answered "yes" to the question, "Are you providing obstetric deliveries as a routine part of your practice?" and who reported a primary practice area of family medicine, obstetrics & gynecology, obstetics, gynecology, or maternal fetal medicine. County population estimates are derived from the US Census 2016 Population Estimate Program.

column3: % of adults who are current smokers
column109: Adult Smoking is based on CDC BRFSS data; the CDC produces single-year estimates at the county level using a combination of BRFSS data and a multilevel modeling approach based on respondent answers and individual characteristics such as age and sex and race/ethnicity, along with county-level poverty and county and state-level contextual effects.

column3: % of high school students reporting current use of any tobacco product
column5: Special data request from NC Division of Public Health, Tobacco Prevention and Control Branch
column109: Data are reported aggregated in three regions (East, West, Central); *estimates for the Central Region are not representative of the total population due to low response rate; Current use refers to any use in the past 30 days.

column3: Unintentional poisoning mortality rate per 100,000 population
column109: Deaths included are those with unintentional poisoning as first listed cause of death.

column3: Rate of opiate poisoning deaths per 100,000 population
column109: Reflects opiate deaths by all intents. Deaths included are those with any mention of opium, heroin, other opioids, methadone, and/or other synthetic opioid. Counts by any mention of drug type are not mutally exclusive; if a death involved multiple drugs it could be listed in additional tables

column3: Rate of retail opioid prescriptions dispensed per 100 persons
column109: Source for prescribing data: IQVIA Xponent 2006–2019. IQVIA Xponent is based on a sample of approximately 49,900 retail (non-hospital) pharmacies, which dispense nearly 92% of all retail prescriptions in the United States. For this database, a prescription is a new or refill prescription dispensed at a retail pharmacy in the sample and paid for by commercial insurance, Medicaid, Medicare, cash or its equivalent, and other third-party coverage. This database does not include mail order prescriptions. For the calculation of dispensing rates, numerators are the projected total number of opioid prescriptions dispensed annually at the state, county, or national level. Annual resident population denominators were obtained from the U.S. Census Bureau. Opioid prescriptions were identified using the National Drug Code.

column3: Rate of substance abuse and mental health-related visits to emergency departments per 100,000 population
column5: Special data request from NC Hospital Association
column109: Rates are calculated using the number of emergency department discharges with a diagnosis of mental health or substance abuse disorder and 2016 population estimates from the US Census Population Estimates Program. To avoid hospital identification through county-level reporting, rates are aggregated into LME/MCO region based on the ZIP code of the patient.

column3: Cancer incidence rates per 100,000 population
column4: NC State Center for Health Statistics
column109:
Rates are calculated using the bridged-race population estimates obtained from the National Center for Health Statistics. Age-adjusted to the 2000 U.S. Census; Age-adjusted rates are point estimates. The standard error (SE) for an age-adjusted rate defines the variability in this point estimate. 95% Confidence Interval (CI) based on a formula for estimating the (SE) is provided to illustrate how precise an estimate is; the wider the CI range, the less precise the estimate
and the more the estimate could vary. Age-adjusted rates for two different populations are significantly different when 95% confidence intervals for their age-adjusted rates do not overlap. CI should be framed in the following statement: We are 95 percent confident that the age-adjusted rate for the given
population is between Lower_CI and Upper_C

column109: County-level enrollment in 4 or 5-star centers, December 2020

column3: % of population that is food insecure
column109:
Map the Meal Gap's food insecurity rates are determined using data from the 2009-2018 Current Population Survey on individuals in food insecure households; data from the 2014-2018 American Community Survey (5-year estimates); and 2018 data from the Bureau of Labor Statistics on unemployment rates. 
Numbers reflect percentage of food insecure individuals living in households with incomes within the income bands indicated. Eligibility for federal nutrition programs is 
determined in part by these income thresholds which can vary by state.
Population and food insecurity data in the state totals row do not reflect the sum of all counties in that state. The state totals are aggregated from the congressional 
districts data in that state. All data in the state totals row pertaining to the cost of food or the "Meal Gap" reflect state-level data and are not aggregations of either 
counties or congressional districts.

column2: Low Access to a Grocery Store
column3: % of population with low access to a grocery store
column109: Low-access is defined as living more than 1 mile from a supermarket or large grocery store if in an urban area, or more than 10 miles from a supermarket or large grocery store if in a rural area.

column3: % of households without access to a vehicle
Violent crime rate per 100,000 population
column109: The crime rate is defined as the number of offenses per 100,000 population. The population figures used to calculate population coverage and crime rates are based on population data from the NC Office of State Budget, Planning, and Management. Violent crime includes the offenses of murder, rape, robbery, and aggravated assault. Data is partially reported (not full 12 months of reported data) for over 50% of the county population for 2019 for Caswell County. Data is for full 12 month period for over 50 percent of the county population for 2019 for Beaufort, Brusnwick, Clay, Columbus, Davie, Gates, Halifax, Harnett, Henderson, Hoke, Hyde, Jones, Lenoir, Martin, Nash, Northampton, Pender, Perquimans, Randolph, Rutherford, Stokes, Surry, and Washington Counties. Crimes reported in Rocky Mount have been separated into county of occurrence for Edgecombe and Nash Counties.

column3: Average daily density of fine particulate matter in micrograms per cubic meter
column109: County-level estimates are modeled from EPA air monitors and seasonal averages. EPA monitors are limited by their locations, measuring only up to a certain distance in any direction, and their sampling structure, from one sample every day to once per week.
